ce:section.ce:para:
At the present work, PEI and CA as precursors were adopted to synthesize C-dots. The reaction was firstly condensed between CA and PEI, whereupon they formed polymer-like composites, which were then carbonized to form the C-dots (see Scheme 1
                        ). XPS was employed to provide convincing evidences for the surface state of C-dots. The XPS spectrum of C-dots exhibits the as-prepared C-dots is composed of carbon, oxygen, and nitrogen. The obvious C, N and O peaks were detected with binding energy at around 285 eV, and 399.5 and 531.3 eV, respectively (see Fig. 1
                        A). The high-resolution C1s analysis revealed three peaks observed with the binding energies of about 284.6, 286.0 and 287.5 eV are attributed to C-C/CC, C-N and CO species, respectively (see Fig. 1B) [31]. The characteristic peak of CC sp2 at 284.6 eV indicates the abundant graphite structure of C-dots [41]. SEM images of C-dots gave the same chemical component as XPS (see Fig. S1). Moreover, the surface groups were also investigated by FTIR spectrum (see Fig. 1C). The peak from 1350 to 1490 cm−1 can be identified as COO- group [42]. A small band from 2810 to 2950 cm−1 is ascribed to the C-H bonds. A sharp peak associated with amide linkage (–CONH–), bending vibration of –NH and asymmetric stretching vibrations of C-NH-C were found at 1662, 1564 and 1127 cm−1, respectively [31,41,43]. In addition, the broad peak around 3425 cm−1 occurs at FTIR curve because of the stretching vibrations of C-OH bonds. The band ranging from 750 to 890 cm−1 is the C-H bending vibration [40]. As shown in Fig. S2, the zeta potential of the C-dots was detected as +6.5 mV, suggesting C-dots are positively charged due to large amount of amine and a little carboxylic groups anchoring on the surface of the C-dots. The above results indicate the as-prepared C-dots are directly functionalized by large amount of amine and little carboxylic acid in the synthesis process without any additional surface modification (see Scheme 1). The XRD pattern of the C-dots shown in Fig. S3A displays a broad peak at about 24.1°, which is possibly attributed to highly disordered carbon atoms. TEM image of the C-dots can be seen to have a uniform dispersion without apparent aggregation and particle size of 2–6 nm in diameter (see Fig. S3B). The high-resolution TEM do not reveal any clear lattice fringe, indicating its amorphous nature, which is in good agreement with XRD result.
